ce:section.ce:para:
Ultraviolet (UV) photodetectors are essential in various applications such as environmental inspection, missile technology, space research, high temperature flame detection and optical communications [1]. Schottky junction UV photodetectors are usually fabricated with a semiconductor material of wide optical band gap (3–4eV) and a metal contact of large work function (e.g. Platinum, Gold, silver, Iridium, palladium etc.) [2–4]. Zinc oxide (ZnO) is an important wide band gap semiconductor (3.2–3.4eV) [5,6] with superior photoconductivity [7], and have been studied in photodetectors, sensors and piezo-phototronics [8–10] applications. ZnO/metal Schottky junction UV photodetectors are particularly attractive due to its large band gap along with easy synthesis process and environmental friendly nature. Deposition of metal contacts usually needs high vacuum techniques and several lithographic steps, which increases the fabrication cost of the device. Recently, instead of using expensive metal electrodes, a hole conducting polymer poly(3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene) polystyrene sulfonate (PEDOT:PSS) was utilized as an alternative electrical contact with ZnO thin films and nanostructures [5,11]. PEDOT:PSS can serve the role of transparent metal contacts as it has large work function (∼5–5.4eV) [6,12], high transmittance (>90%) [11,13] in a wide range of spectrum (250–800nm) [11] and superior electrical conductivity (1–4000Scm−1) [14,15]. Moreover, such semiconductor/conducting polymer Schottky junction can be made by simple spin coating or drop casting on solid or flexible substrates. Nowadays, graphene and carbon based nanomaterials have been studied as photosensitizer for enhancing the photoresponse properties of the UV detectors [16–19]. In our previous report, we have studied ZnO nanorod/PEDOT:PSS based Schottky junction UV detectors with high external quantum efficiency (EQE), detectivity (Dλ
                     ) and responsivity (Rλ
                     ) [5]. The photodetector parameters EQE, Dλ
                      and (Rλ
                     ) have been further enhanced several times after sensitizing the nanorods with graphene quantum dots (GQDs). The superior UV detector performance was attributed to the strong UV photoabsorption of GQDs [20–23]. It has been observed that, the photoabsorption of GQDs can be further increased from UV–vis range by adding several impurity atoms like, B, N, S etc. [24–30]. Here, we have studied the photodetector properties of nitrogen doped graphene quantum dots (NGQDs) decorated ZnO nanorods/PEDOT:PSS Schottky junction diode. The key photodetector parameters such as EQE, detectivity, responsivity, response and recovery time have been improved significantly using NGQD decorated ZnO NRs.
